You should always look at your diagnostics before your results. The negative kV is not the thing to note here; your time-series plots don’t look anything like the references, and indicate something is very wrong with your data recording.

It is not possible to say what is wrong exactly from the SysId interface alone, and I suspect you would be better-served by manual tuning at this point.

I do not; the tutorials on frc-docs are all we have right now. I know @DeltaDizzy is working on a much-needed rewrite of those, but I don’t think that will necessarily involve subsystem-specific example code.

As I mentioned in my PSA thread on SysId, it’s really hard/impossible to use the tool if you can’t understand the diagnostics panel and troubleshoot it yourself. I’d only put effort into SysId tuning if you’ve finished almost everything else.

If you do pursue SysId, try to build your skill at viewing and interpreting robot telemetry before you open the logs in the tool, to verify that the data streams look like you think they should. If you don’t know what they should look like, reason about it from the principles you understand about manual tuning.

You also must understand what the dimensions of your gains (feedforward and feedback) are, and how to convert the gains between different unit systems, in order to do anything other than manual tuning.
